o   Enos  . While this is linguistically possible there is no evidence yet to show that it was the origin of the surname."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Penella","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Enrico, Gino, Italo, Marco, Mauro, Nicola, Remo, Salvatore.","Italian: from a female derivative of the personal name   Pero  .","Catalan: habitational name from any of various places called Perella, in the Vallespir, Solsonè, and Ripollès areas (northern Catalonia) and also in Minorca."],"variants":[{"name":"Parella","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Gaetano, Armando, Carmine, Gilberto, Mario, Rocco, Salvatore.","Catalan: variant of   Perella  .","Catalan: apparently also a topographic name, from <i>pareja</i> ‘pair’, as a medieval land measurement denoting the area of land that could be plowed by a pair of oxen in one day."]},{"name":"Pero","meanings":["Italian: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, a variant of <i>Piero</i> ‘Peter’ (see   Pieri  ).","Galician: from the personal name <i>Pero</i>, Galician equivalent of   Peter  .","Portuguese: habitational name from any of the places called Pero."]}]},{"name":"Teresa","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Theresa .  In the English-speaking world the name is often chosen in this spelling by Roman Catholics, with particular reference to the Spanish saint, Teresa of Ávila (  Teresa Cepeda de Ahumada ,  1515–82 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Theresa","meanings":["Of problematic origin. The name seems to have been first used in Spain and Portugal, and, according to tradition, was the name of the wife of St Paulinus of Nola, who spent most of his life in Spain; she was said to have originated (and to have derived her name) from the Greek island of <i>Thēra</i>. However, this story is neither factually nor etymologically confirmed."]},{"name":"Teresia","meanings":["Of problematic origin. The name seems to have been first used in Spain and Portugal, and, according to tradition, was the name of the wife of St Paulinus of Nola, who spent most of his life in Spain; she was said to have originated (and to have derived her name) from the Greek island of <i>Thēra</i>. However, this story is neither factually nor etymologically confirmed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"D. Teresa Annes de Penella was born about 1150, in Alto Alentejo, Portugal as the daughter of João Annes de Vasconcellos. She had at least 4 sons and 2 daughters with D. Soeiro Nunes Velho. She died in 1190, at the age of 41."},"et":{"aproximadamente 1150–1190":"umbes 1150–1190","1150–1190":"1150–1190","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1170–Male":"1170–Surnud","1173–Male":"1173–Surnud","1175–Female":"1175–Surnud","1176–Male":"1176–Surnud","1180–Female":"1180–Surnud","1183–Male":"1183–Surnud","1125–Male":"1125–Surnud","1190":"1190","about 1170":"umbes 1170","aproximadamente 1150":"umbes 1150","1176":"1176","1175":"1175","1173":"1173","1183":"1183","1150":"1150","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","Abt 1173":"umbes 1173","um 1180":"umbes 1180","Abt 1183":"umbes 1183","1125":"1125","um 1175":"umbes 1175","1145":"1145","Baião, Faro, Portugal":"Baião, Faro, Portugal","Of,,, Por